Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil over high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat and add the @British pork mince{240%g}. Cook until browned, ~{2-3%mins}. Break it up with a #spoon{} as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Drain and discard any excess fat from the pork.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Add the garlic and sprinkle over the @Italian style herbs{1%tsp}. Cook, stirring, for another ~{1%minute}.

Meanwhile, add the @penne pasta{180%g} to the saucepan of boiling water and cook until tender, ~{12%mins}.

When cooked, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the saucepan, drizzle with a little @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, add the @Worcester sauce{15%ml} to the pork, stir and allow to bubble away until evaporated, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @finely chopped tomatoes{1%tin}, @red wine stock paste{28%g}, @water{50%ml} and a pinch of @sugar{pinch}.

Bring to the boil, stirring, then reduce the heat to medium and simmer rapidly until the sauce thickens, ~{5-6%mins}.

> TIP: Add a splash more water if it gets too thick.

While the sauce cooks, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g}.

When the sauce is cooked, add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the sauce a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

Toss the drained penne through the sauce along with half of the cheddar.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed.

Serve the porky penne in bowls finished with a sprinkle of the remaining cheddar. Enjoy!